        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Imaging for Cardiac Valve Interventions</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Oct 13 2014</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name">Demonstration of Mitral Valve Prolapse with CT for Planning of Mitral Valve Repair</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Hyun Jung</span> <span property="familyName">Koo</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Dong Hyun</span> <span property="familyName">Yang</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#fd9992939a95848893d3849c939abd9a909c9491d39e9290" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="2d4942434a4554584303544c434a6d4a404c4441034e4240">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Sang Young</span> <span property="familyName">Oh</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Joon-Won</span> <span property="familyName">Kang</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Dae-Hee</span> <span property="familyName">Kim</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Jae-Kwan</span> <span property="familyName">Song</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con7"><span property="givenName">Jae Won</span> <span property="familyName">Lee</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con8"><span property="givenName">Cheol Hyun</span> <span property="familyName">Chung</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con9"><span property="givenName">Tae-Hwan</span> <span property="familyName">Lim</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">34</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">6</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.346130146" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.346130146</a></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Mitral valve prolapse (MVP), the most frequent cause of severe nonischemic mitral regurgitation, often warrants surgical or interventional valve repair. The severity of mitral regurgitation positively correlates with the development of heart failure and death. Even in patients who are asymptomatic, severe mitral regurgitation causes higher rates of death, heart failure, and atrial fibrillation. Repair procedures for mitral regurgitation have progressed to include leaflet repair, chordal transfer, ring or band annuloplasty, and new percutaneous procedures. In planning for mitral valve repair, detection and localization of mitral valve abnormalities are important. The causes of mitral regurgitation include degenerative mitral valve (eg, prolapsed leaflet, myxomatous degeneration, and Barlow disease [excessive degenerated tissues with elongated chordae]). Cardiac computed tomography (CT) is helpful for depicting mitral valve abnormalities. It allows complete visualization of cardiac anatomic features, including the coronary arteries, paravalvular structures, and cardiac wall motion. This review addresses the role of cardiac CT in depicting anatomic features of the mitral valve, provides a practical method for localizing the exact site of MVP, and discusses the CT findings of various causes of mitral regurgitation. The first step in reconstructing CT images for MVP is to select the best cardiac phase for depicting the anatomic features of the mitral valve. Additional views of the mitral valve then show the specific mitral valve abnormality. This article provides technical tips for demonstrating MVP with CT, as well as imaging results for various causes of MVP and intraoperative findings. <i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.346130146">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.346130146">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig1a.jpeg" height="912" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Anterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse in a patient with a heart rate of 70 beats per minute. <b>(a)</b> Prospective ECG-triggered sequential cardiac CT image, obtained in the cardiac phase from 250 to 350 msec and reconstructed at 10-msec intervals, shows the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Prospective ECG-triggered sequential cardiac CT image, obtained in the cardiac phase from 250 to 350 msec and reconstructed at 10-msec intervals, shows the mitral valve (arrow). The ECG image at bottom shows the interval of image acquisition. In this patient, the best phase for visualizing the mitral valve is at 300 msec. The image quality for both the coronary artery and mitral valve is acceptable, and the radiation dose was reasonably low (dose-length product, 163 mGy × cm; effective dose, 2.3 mSv). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig1b.jpeg" height="912" width="660" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Anterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse in a patient with a heart rate of 70 beats per minute. <b>(a)</b> Prospective ECG-triggered sequential cardiac CT image, obtained in the cardiac phase from 250 to 350 msec and reconstructed at 10-msec intervals, shows the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Prospective ECG-triggered sequential cardiac CT image, obtained in the cardiac phase from 250 to 350 msec and reconstructed at 10-msec intervals, shows the mitral valve (arrow). The ECG image at bottom shows the interval of image acquisition. In this patient, the best phase for visualizing the mitral valve is at 300 msec. The image quality for both the coronary artery and mitral valve is acceptable, and the radiation dose was reasonably low (dose-length product, 163 mGy × cm; effective dose, 2.3 mSv). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig2.jpeg" height="512" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Three-chamber views in a patient with MVP. Cardiac CT images obtained in the various systolic phases show MVP (arrow). The image obtained at 25% of the R-R interval has the best image quality. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig3a.jpeg" height="628" width="759" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Generation of the en face view. <b>(a)</b> Standard axial CT image shows the mitral valve. The solid line is used to obtain the two-chamber view, and the dashed line shows the mitral annular plane. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>DA</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber CT image shows the mitral annular plane (dashed line), left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, and left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The en face view is obtained by using the parallel images obtained at the level of the mitral annular plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Functional mitral regurgitation resulting from idiopathic left ventricular dilatation in a 72-year-old man. En face illustration <b>(c)</b> and CT image <b>(d)</b> show the simulated surgical view of the mitral plane. Note the linear coaptation defect (arrow in <b>d</b>) between the anterior and posterior mitral valve leaflets. The left atrial appendage (<i>LAA</i>) and left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) are landmarks for the lateral portion of the mitral annulus. In the en face CT image, the aorta (<i>Ao</i>) and mitral annular plane are pear shaped (dashed line in <b>d</b>). The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in these images. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively; <i>TV</i> = tricuspic valve. <b>(e)</b> Illustration shows the surgeon’s approach to the mitral valve. The en face CT image <b>(d)</b> of the mitral valve derives from the surgeon’s approach. The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in this image. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig3b.jpeg" height="627" width="815" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Generation of the en face view. <b>(a)</b> Standard axial CT image shows the mitral valve. The solid line is used to obtain the two-chamber view, and the dashed line shows the mitral annular plane. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>DA</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber CT image shows the mitral annular plane (dashed line), left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, and left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The en face view is obtained by using the parallel images obtained at the level of the mitral annular plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Functional mitral regurgitation resulting from idiopathic left ventricular dilatation in a 72-year-old man. En face illustration <b>(c)</b> and CT image <b>(d)</b> show the simulated surgical view of the mitral plane. Note the linear coaptation defect (arrow in <b>d</b>) between the anterior and posterior mitral valve leaflets. The left atrial appendage (<i>LAA</i>) and left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) are landmarks for the lateral portion of the mitral annulus. In the en face CT image, the aorta (<i>Ao</i>) and mitral annular plane are pear shaped (dashed line in <b>d</b>). The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in these images. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively; <i>TV</i> = tricuspic valve. <b>(e)</b> Illustration shows the surgeon’s approach to the mitral valve. The en face CT image <b>(d)</b> of the mitral valve derives from the surgeon’s approach. The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in this image. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig3c.jpeg" height="656" width="645" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Generation of the en face view. <b>(a)</b> Standard axial CT image shows the mitral valve. The solid line is used to obtain the two-chamber view, and the dashed line shows the mitral annular plane. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>DA</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber CT image shows the mitral annular plane (dashed line), left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, and left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The en face view is obtained by using the parallel images obtained at the level of the mitral annular plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Functional mitral regurgitation resulting from idiopathic left ventricular dilatation in a 72-year-old man. En face illustration <b>(c)</b> and CT image <b>(d)</b> show the simulated surgical view of the mitral plane. Note the linear coaptation defect (arrow in <b>d</b>) between the anterior and posterior mitral valve leaflets. The left atrial appendage (<i>LAA</i>) and left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) are landmarks for the lateral portion of the mitral annulus. In the en face CT image, the aorta (<i>Ao</i>) and mitral annular plane are pear shaped (dashed line in <b>d</b>). The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in these images. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively; <i>TV</i> = tricuspic valve. <b>(e)</b> Illustration shows the surgeon’s approach to the mitral valve. The en face CT image <b>(d)</b> of the mitral valve derives from the surgeon’s approach. The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in this image. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig3d.jpeg" height="656" width="582" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Generation of the en face view. <b>(a)</b> Standard axial CT image shows the mitral valve. The solid line is used to obtain the two-chamber view, and the dashed line shows the mitral annular plane. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>DA</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber CT image shows the mitral annular plane (dashed line), left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, and left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The en face view is obtained by using the parallel images obtained at the level of the mitral annular plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Functional mitral regurgitation resulting from idiopathic left ventricular dilatation in a 72-year-old man. En face illustration <b>(c)</b> and CT image <b>(d)</b> show the simulated surgical view of the mitral plane. Note the linear coaptation defect (arrow in <b>d</b>) between the anterior and posterior mitral valve leaflets. The left atrial appendage (<i>LAA</i>) and left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) are landmarks for the lateral portion of the mitral annulus. In the en face CT image, the aorta (<i>Ao</i>) and mitral annular plane are pear shaped (dashed line in <b>d</b>). The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in these images. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively; <i>TV</i> = tricuspic valve. <b>(e)</b> Illustration shows the surgeon’s approach to the mitral valve. The en face CT image <b>(d)</b> of the mitral valve derives from the surgeon’s approach. The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in this image. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig3e.jpeg" height="656" width="621" aria-labelledby="fig3e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span> Generation of the en face view. <b>(a)</b> Standard axial CT image shows the mitral valve. The solid line is used to obtain the two-chamber view, and the dashed line shows the mitral annular plane. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>DA</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber CT image shows the mitral annular plane (dashed line), left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, and left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The en face view is obtained by using the parallel images obtained at the level of the mitral annular plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Functional mitral regurgitation resulting from idiopathic left ventricular dilatation in a 72-year-old man. En face illustration <b>(c)</b> and CT image <b>(d)</b> show the simulated surgical view of the mitral plane. Note the linear coaptation defect (arrow in <b>d</b>) between the anterior and posterior mitral valve leaflets. The left atrial appendage (<i>LAA</i>) and left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) are landmarks for the lateral portion of the mitral annulus. In the en face CT image, the aorta (<i>Ao</i>) and mitral annular plane are pear shaped (dashed line in <b>d</b>). The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in these images. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively; <i>TV</i> = tricuspic valve. <b>(e)</b> Illustration shows the surgeon’s approach to the mitral valve. The en face CT image <b>(d)</b> of the mitral valve derives from the surgeon’s approach. The Carpentier nomenclature system for the mitral valve leaflet scallop is used in this image. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig3e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig4a.jpeg" height="800" width="596" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Reconstruction of CT images of the mitral valve to evaluate the extent and location of disease in a 41-year-old man with MVP. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively. <b>(a)</b> Axial diagram at the level of the mitral valve (top) and parasagittal diagram (bottom; cf <a href="#fig2">Fig 2</a>) perpendicular to the mitral valve coaptation line on the en face view show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Parasagittal reconstructed CT image shows MVP in the anterior leaflet <i>(A)</i> of the mitral valve (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>P</i> = posterior leaflet. <b>(c)</b> Coronal diagram (top) parallel to the line connecting the medial and lateral commissures on the en face view and coronal diagram (bottom) show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image shows a prolapsed scallop of the mitral valve (arrow) near the left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, which is a landmark of a lateral direction in the mitral valve annulus. The proximal left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) is also located in the lateral direction, and the coronary sinus <i>(CS)</i> and interatrial septum are located in the medial direction. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(e)</b> Coronal thin-section maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image obtained at the level of the valve shows the section thickness used to generate the surgeon’s view. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(f)</b> Surgeon’s view of the mitral valve obtained with thin-section (15-mm) volume rendering shows that the A1 scallop is prolapsed (arrow, white lines). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet. <b>(g)</b> Intraoperative photograph obtained with a robot-assisted surgery system shows that the locations of the prolapsed scallop (<i>A1</i>, white lines) and left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i> correspond with the CT findings. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig4b.jpeg" height="770" width="647" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Reconstruction of CT images of the mitral valve to evaluate the extent and location of disease in a 41-year-old man with MVP. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively. <b>(a)</b> Axial diagram at the level of the mitral valve (top) and parasagittal diagram (bottom; cf <a href="#fig2">Fig 2</a>) perpendicular to the mitral valve coaptation line on the en face view show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Parasagittal reconstructed CT image shows MVP in the anterior leaflet <i>(A)</i> of the mitral valve (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>P</i> = posterior leaflet. <b>(c)</b> Coronal diagram (top) parallel to the line connecting the medial and lateral commissures on the en face view and coronal diagram (bottom) show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image shows a prolapsed scallop of the mitral valve (arrow) near the left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, which is a landmark of a lateral direction in the mitral valve annulus. The proximal left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) is also located in the lateral direction, and the coronary sinus <i>(CS)</i> and interatrial septum are located in the medial direction. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(e)</b> Coronal thin-section maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image obtained at the level of the valve shows the section thickness used to generate the surgeon’s view. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(f)</b> Surgeon’s view of the mitral valve obtained with thin-section (15-mm) volume rendering shows that the A1 scallop is prolapsed (arrow, white lines). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet. <b>(g)</b> Intraoperative photograph obtained with a robot-assisted surgery system shows that the locations of the prolapsed scallop (<i>A1</i>, white lines) and left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i> correspond with the CT findings. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig4c.jpeg" height="768" width="732" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Reconstruction of CT images of the mitral valve to evaluate the extent and location of disease in a 41-year-old man with MVP. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively. <b>(a)</b> Axial diagram at the level of the mitral valve (top) and parasagittal diagram (bottom; cf <a href="#fig2">Fig 2</a>) perpendicular to the mitral valve coaptation line on the en face view show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Parasagittal reconstructed CT image shows MVP in the anterior leaflet <i>(A)</i> of the mitral valve (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>P</i> = posterior leaflet. <b>(c)</b> Coronal diagram (top) parallel to the line connecting the medial and lateral commissures on the en face view and coronal diagram (bottom) show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image shows a prolapsed scallop of the mitral valve (arrow) near the left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, which is a landmark of a lateral direction in the mitral valve annulus. The proximal left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) is also located in the lateral direction, and the coronary sinus <i>(CS)</i> and interatrial septum are located in the medial direction. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(e)</b> Coronal thin-section maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image obtained at the level of the valve shows the section thickness used to generate the surgeon’s view. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(f)</b> Surgeon’s view of the mitral valve obtained with thin-section (15-mm) volume rendering shows that the A1 scallop is prolapsed (arrow, white lines). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet. <b>(g)</b> Intraoperative photograph obtained with a robot-assisted surgery system shows that the locations of the prolapsed scallop (<i>A1</i>, white lines) and left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i> correspond with the CT findings. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig4d.jpeg" height="770" width="681" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> Reconstruction of CT images of the mitral valve to evaluate the extent and location of disease in a 41-year-old man with MVP. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively. <b>(a)</b> Axial diagram at the level of the mitral valve (top) and parasagittal diagram (bottom; cf <a href="#fig2">Fig 2</a>) perpendicular to the mitral valve coaptation line on the en face view show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Parasagittal reconstructed CT image shows MVP in the anterior leaflet <i>(A)</i> of the mitral valve (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>P</i> = posterior leaflet. <b>(c)</b> Coronal diagram (top) parallel to the line connecting the medial and lateral commissures on the en face view and coronal diagram (bottom) show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image shows a prolapsed scallop of the mitral valve (arrow) near the left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, which is a landmark of a lateral direction in the mitral valve annulus. The proximal left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) is also located in the lateral direction, and the coronary sinus <i>(CS)</i> and interatrial septum are located in the medial direction. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(e)</b> Coronal thin-section maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image obtained at the level of the valve shows the section thickness used to generate the surgeon’s view. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(f)</b> Surgeon’s view of the mitral valve obtained with thin-section (15-mm) volume rendering shows that the A1 scallop is prolapsed (arrow, white lines). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet. <b>(g)</b> Intraoperative photograph obtained with a robot-assisted surgery system shows that the locations of the prolapsed scallop (<i>A1</i>, white lines) and left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i> correspond with the CT findings. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href=