<img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig4g.jpeg" height="632" width="566" aria-labelledby="fig4g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4g</span> Reconstruction of CT images of the mitral valve to evaluate the extent and location of disease in a 41-year-old man with MVP. <i>A1</i>, <i>A2</i>, and <i>A3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the anterior leaflet, respectively; <i>P1</i>, <i>P2</i>, and <i>P3</i> = lateral, middle, and medial scallops of the posterior leaflet, respectively. <b>(a)</b> Axial diagram at the level of the mitral valve (top) and parasagittal diagram (bottom; cf <a href="#fig2">Fig 2</a>) perpendicular to the mitral valve coaptation line on the en face view show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Parasagittal reconstructed CT image shows MVP in the anterior leaflet <i>(A)</i> of the mitral valve (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>P</i> = posterior leaflet. <b>(c)</b> Coronal diagram (top) parallel to the line connecting the medial and lateral commissures on the en face view and coronal diagram (bottom) show the mitral valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image shows a prolapsed scallop of the mitral valve (arrow) near the left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>, which is a landmark of a lateral direction in the mitral valve annulus. The proximal left circumflex artery (<i>LCx</i>) is also located in the lateral direction, and the coronary sinus <i>(CS)</i> and interatrial septum are located in the medial direction. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(e)</b> Coronal thin-section maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image obtained at the level of the valve shows the section thickness used to generate the surgeon’s view. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(f)</b> Surgeon’s view of the mitral valve obtained with thin-section (15-mm) volume rendering shows that the A1 scallop is prolapsed (arrow, white lines). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet. <b>(g)</b> Intraoperative photograph obtained with a robot-assisted surgery system shows that the locations of the prolapsed scallop (<i>A1</i>, white lines) and left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i> correspond with the CT findings. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>P1</i> = lateral scallop of the posterior leaflet.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig4g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig5a.jpeg" height="993" width="657" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 56-year-old man with posterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows prolapse of the posterior leaflet (isolated prolapse of the middle scallop in the posterior leaflet; simple lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the prolapse (arrow) is located in the middle scallop. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view shows the three-dimensional relationship between the prolapsed scallop (arrows) and mitral annulus (Movie 2). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows that the prolapsed scallop corresponds with the findings seen on the surgeon’s view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig5b.jpeg" height="993" width="667" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 56-year-old man with posterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows prolapse of the posterior leaflet (isolated prolapse of the middle scallop in the posterior leaflet; simple lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the prolapse (arrow) is located in the middle scallop. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view shows the three-dimensional relationship between the prolapsed scallop (arrows) and mitral annulus (Movie 2). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows that the prolapsed scallop corresponds with the findings seen on the surgeon’s view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig5c.jpeg" height="640" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 56-year-old man with posterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows prolapse of the posterior leaflet (isolated prolapse of the middle scallop in the posterior leaflet; simple lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the prolapse (arrow) is located in the middle scallop. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view shows the three-dimensional relationship between the prolapsed scallop (arrows) and mitral annulus (Movie 2). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows that the prolapsed scallop corresponds with the findings seen on the surgeon’s view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig5d.jpeg" height="640" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 56-year-old man with posterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows prolapse of the posterior leaflet (isolated prolapse of the middle scallop in the posterior leaflet; simple lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the prolapse (arrow) is located in the middle scallop. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view shows the three-dimensional relationship between the prolapsed scallop (arrows) and mitral annulus (Movie 2). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows that the prolapsed scallop corresponds with the findings seen on the surgeon’s view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig6a.jpeg" height="833" width="796" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 54-year-old man with anterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal view of the mitral valve shows severe prolapse of the anterior leaflet (A3 and A2; complex lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows severe prolapse of the medial (A3) scallop (straight arrow) and mild prolapse of the middle (A2) scallop (curved arrow). The lateral (A1) scallop (*) has a relatively normal shape. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (Movie 3). Curved arrow = A2, straight arrow = A3, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(e)</b> CT image shows that the atrial septal defect (arrowheads) is combined with MVP. Atrial septal defect is a predisposing factor for MVP because it alters the geometric features of the left ventricle. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig6b.jpeg" height="833" width="677" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 54-year-old man with anterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal view of the mitral valve shows severe prolapse of the anterior leaflet (A3 and A2; complex lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows severe prolapse of the medial (A3) scallop (straight arrow) and mild prolapse of the middle (A2) scallop (curved arrow). The lateral (A1) scallop (*) has a relatively normal shape. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (Movie 3). Curved arrow = A2, straight arrow = A3, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(e)</b> CT image shows that the atrial septal defect (arrowheads) is combined with MVP. Atrial septal defect is a predisposing factor for MVP because it alters the geometric features of the left ventricle. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig6c.jpeg" height="640" width="649" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 54-year-old man with anterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal view of the mitral valve shows severe prolapse of the anterior leaflet (A3 and A2; complex lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows severe prolapse of the medial (A3) scallop (straight arrow) and mild prolapse of the middle (A2) scallop (curved arrow). The lateral (A1) scallop (*) has a relatively normal shape. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (Movie 3). Curved arrow = A2, straight arrow = A3, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(e)</b> CT image shows that the atrial septal defect (arrowheads) is combined with MVP. Atrial septal defect is a predisposing factor for MVP because it alters the geometric features of the left ventricle. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig6d.jpeg" height="640" width="825" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 54-year-old man with anterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal view of the mitral valve shows severe prolapse of the anterior leaflet (A3 and A2; complex lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows severe prolapse of the medial (A3) scallop (straight arrow) and mild prolapse of the middle (A2) scallop (curved arrow). The lateral (A1) scallop (*) has a relatively normal shape. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (Movie 3). Curved arrow = A2, straight arrow = A3, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(e)</b> CT image shows that the atrial septal defect (arrowheads) is combined with MVP. Atrial septal defect is a predisposing factor for MVP because it alters the geometric features of the left ventricle. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig6e.jpeg" height="639" width="796" aria-labelledby="fig6e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6e</span> Step-by-step approach to image reconstruction in a 54-year-old man with anterior mitral valve leaflet prolapse. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal view of the mitral valve shows severe prolapse of the anterior leaflet (A3 and A2; complex lesion) (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows severe prolapse of the medial (A3) scallop (straight arrow) and mild prolapse of the middle (A2) scallop (curved arrow). The lateral (A1) scallop (*) has a relatively normal shape. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (Movie 3). Curved arrow = A2, straight arrow = A3, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(e)</b> CT image shows that the atrial septal defect (arrowheads) is combined with MVP. Atrial septal defect is a predisposing factor for MVP because it alters the geometric features of the left ventricle. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig6e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig7a.jpeg" height="879" width="646" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> MVP involving the posterior scallop in a 41-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows superior displacement of the posterior leaflet (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the main prolapsed segment (arrow) is the middle (P2) scallop. The base of the prolapse is wider than is usually seen with an isolated prolapse of the P2 scallop (cf <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5</a>) and extends to the medial scallop (arrowhead). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show the prolapsed segment of the P2 scallop (Movie 4). Medial extension of the prolapse (arrowhead) is better seen at CT than at echocardiography. Arrow = prolapsed posterior leaflet of the mitral valve, <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig7b.jpeg" height="879" width="674" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> MVP involving the posterior scallop in a 41-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows superior displacement of the posterior leaflet (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the main prolapsed segment (arrow) is the middle (P2) scallop. The base of the prolapse is wider than is usually seen with an isolated prolapse of the P2 scallop (cf <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5</a>) and extends to the medial scallop (arrowhead). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show the prolapsed segment of the P2 scallop (Movie 4). Medial extension of the prolapse (arrowhead) is better seen at CT than at echocardiography. Arrow = prolapsed posterior leaflet of the mitral valve, <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig7c.jpeg" height="583" width="615" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> MVP involving the posterior scallop in a 41-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows superior displacement of the posterior leaflet (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the main prolapsed segment (arrow) is the middle (P2) scallop. The base of the prolapse is wider than is usually seen with an isolated prolapse of the P2 scallop (cf <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5</a>) and extends to the medial scallop (arrowhead). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show the prolapsed segment of the P2 scallop (Movie 4). Medial extension of the prolapse (arrowhead) is better seen at CT than at echocardiography. Arrow = prolapsed posterior leaflet of the mitral valve, <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig7d.jpeg" height="585" width="710" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span> MVP involving the posterior scallop in a 41-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows superior displacement of the posterior leaflet (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows that the main prolapsed segment (arrow) is the middle (P2) scallop. The base of the prolapse is wider than is usually seen with an isolated prolapse of the P2 scallop (cf <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5</a>) and extends to the medial scallop (arrowhead). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c, d)</b> Surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> and intraoperative photograph <b>(d)</b> show the prolapsed segment of the P2 scallop (Movie 4). Medial extension of the prolapse (arrowhead) is better seen at CT than at echocardiography. Arrow = prolapsed posterior leaflet of the mitral valve, <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig8a.jpeg" height="848" width="687" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Myxomatous degeneration of the mitral valve in a 46-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows prolapse of the anterior leaflet (straight arrow) and diffuse thickening of the valve leaflet and subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal CT image of the mitral valve <b>(b)</b> and surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> (Movie 5) show that the main location of the prolapsed scallop is A2 (arrow); the A3 scallop (arrowhead) is also involved. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph of the thickened anterior valve leaflet (original magnification, ×100 [inset: magnification, ×40]; hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows diffuse thickening and degeneration of the fibrosa layer, with disintegration of collagen fibers (arrows). The patient underwent mitral valve repair, and a diagnosis of myxomatous degeneration was made.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig8b.jpeg" height="848" width="637" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Myxomatous degeneration of the mitral valve in a 46-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows prolapse of the anterior leaflet (straight arrow) and diffuse thickening of the valve leaflet and subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal CT image of the mitral valve <b>(b)</b> and surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> (Movie 5) show that the main location of the prolapsed scallop is A2 (arrow); the A3 scallop (arrowhead) is also involved. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph of the thickened anterior valve leaflet (original magnification, ×100 [inset: magnification, ×40]; hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows diffuse thickening and degeneration of the fibrosa layer, with disintegration of collagen fibers (arrows). The patient underwent mitral valve repair, and a diagnosis of myxomatous degeneration was made.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig8c.jpeg" height="581" width="613" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Myxomatous degeneration of the mitral valve in a 46-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows prolapse of the anterior leaflet (straight arrow) and diffuse thickening of the valve leaflet and subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal CT image of the mitral valve <b>(b)</b> and surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> (Movie 5) show that the main location of the prolapsed scallop is A2 (arrow); the A3 scallop (arrowhead) is also involved. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph of the thickened anterior valve leaflet (original magnification, ×100 [inset: magnification, ×40]; hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows diffuse thickening and degeneration of the fibrosa layer, with disintegration of collagen fibers (arrows). The patient underwent mitral valve repair, and a diagnosis of myxomatous degeneration was made.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig8d.jpeg" height="581" width="711" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span> Myxomatous degeneration of the mitral valve in a 46-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows prolapse of the anterior leaflet (straight arrow) and diffuse thickening of the valve leaflet and subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal CT image of the mitral valve <b>(b)</b> and surgeon’s view <b>(c)</b> (Movie 5) show that the main location of the prolapsed scallop is A2 (arrow); the A3 scallop (arrowhead) is also involved. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph of the thickened anterior valve leaflet (original magnification, ×100 [inset: magnification, ×40]; hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows diffuse thickening and degeneration of the fibrosa layer, with disintegration of collagen fibers (arrows). The patient underwent mitral valve repair, and a diagnosis of myxomatous degeneration was made.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig9a.jpeg" height="787" width="650" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Barlow disease with extensive prolapse of multiple scallops of the mitral valve in a 50-year-old man with a 3-year history of progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows prolapse of the middle (straight arrow) and medial (*) scallops and diffuse thickening of the chordae tendineae (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT image obtained at the level of the mitral plane shows the mitral valve, which has an irregular “sawing” appearance, and valvular thickening with coaptation failure. Both anterior (arrow) and posterior (arrowhead) leaflets are prolapsed. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 6) clearly shows the extent of disease in both anterior (arrows) and posterior (arrowheads) mitral valve leaflets. Mitral valve replacement was performed because valve repair was not possible. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig9b.jpeg" height="787" width="673" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Barlow disease with extensive prolapse of multiple scallops of the mitral valve in a 50-year-old man with a 3-year history of progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows prolapse of the middle (straight arrow) and medial (*) scallops and diffuse thickening of the chordae tendineae (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT image obtained at the level of the mitral plane shows the mitral valve, which has an irregular “sawing” appearance, and valvular thickening with coaptation failure. Both anterior (arrow) and posterior (arrowhead) leaflets are prolapsed. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 6) clearly shows the extent of disease in both anterior (arrows) and posterior (arrowheads) mitral valve leaflets. Mitral valve replacement was performed because valve repair was not possible. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig9c.jpeg" height="797" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Barlow disease with extensive prolapse of multiple scallops of the mitral valve in a 50-year-old man with a 3-year history of progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows prolapse of the middle (straight arrow) and medial (*) scallops and diffuse thickening of the chordae tendineae (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT image obtained at the level of the mitral plane shows the mitral valve, which has an irregular “sawing” appearance, and valvular thickening with coaptation failure. Both anterior (arrow) and posterior (arrowhead) leaflets are prolapsed. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 6) clearly shows the extent of disease in both anterior (arrows) and posterior (arrowheads) mitral valve leaflets. Mitral valve replacement was performed because valve repair was not possible. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig10a.jpeg" height="988" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Marfan syndrome in a 49-year-old woman with a history of ascending aorta reduction surgery with aortic valvular replacement 8 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image shows diffuse prolapse of both the anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve (arrows) and dilatation of the aortic sinus and surgical ring (arrowheads) at the sinotubular junction, resulting in decreased size of the ascending aorta. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Surgeon’s view shows prolapse of all valve scallops (*, Movie 7). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig10b.jpeg" height="766" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Marfan syndrome in a 49-year-old woman with a history of ascending aorta reduction surgery with aortic valvular replacement 8 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image shows diffuse prolapse of both the anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve (arrows) and dilatation of the aortic sinus and surgical ring (arrowheads) at the sinotubular junction, resulting in decreased size of the ascending aorta. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Surgeon’s view shows prolapse of all valve scallops (*, Movie 7). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig11a.jpeg" height="847" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Coarctation of the aorta in a 17-year-old boy with progressive dyspnea on exertion who received an initial diagnosis of MVP at echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image obtained at the level of the mitral plane shows billowing of the lateral (P1) scallop (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Volume-rendered CT image shows coarctation (arrow) of the aorta (<i>Ao</i>) and dilated collateral vessels (arrowheads). Dilatation of the internal mammary artery (*) is also seen. <i>DA</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>LSA</i> = left subclavian artery, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig11b.jpeg" height="928" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Coarctation of the aorta in a 17-year-old boy with progressive dyspnea on exertion who received an initial diagnosis of MVP at echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image obtained at the level of the mitral plane shows billowing of the lateral (P1) scallop (arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Volume-rendered CT image shows coarctation (arrow) of the aorta (<i>Ao</i>) and dilated collateral vessels (arrowheads). Dilatation of the internal mammary artery (*) is also seen. <i>DA</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>LSA</i> = left subclavian artery, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig12a.jpeg" height="820" width="707" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Rheumatic mitral valve disease with diffuse prolapse of the anterior mitral valve leaflet and chordae rupture in a 36-year-old woman with a history of rheumatic fever 26 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image shows superior bulging of the anterior leaflet (straight arrow) resulting in a coaptation defect (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 8) shows a large coaptation defect (arrow), a result of diffuse prolapse of the anterior mitral valve leaflet <i>(A)</i>. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c)</b> Coronal volume-rendered CT image (Movie 8) shows rupture (arrowhead) and diffuse thickening of the chordae tendineae. <i>A</i> = anterior mitral valve leaflet, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows rupture of the chordae tendineae (arrowhead) and diffuse thickening of the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve <i>(A)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig12b.jpeg" height="820" width="766" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Rheumatic mitral valve disease with diffuse prolapse of the anterior mitral valve leaflet and chordae rupture in a 36-year-old woman with a history of rheumatic fever 26 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image shows superior bulging of the anterior leaflet (straight arrow) resulting in a coaptation defect (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 8) shows a large coaptation defect (arrow), a result of diffuse prolapse of the anterior mitral valve leaflet <i>(A)</i>. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c)</b> Coronal volume-rendered CT image (Movie 8) shows rupture (arrowhead) and diffuse thickening of the chordae tendineae. <i>A</i> = anterior mitral valve leaflet, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows rupture of the chordae tendineae (arrowhead) and diffuse thickening of the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve <i>(A)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig12c.jpeg" height="724" width="563" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Rheumatic mitral valve disease with diffuse prolapse of the anterior mitral valve leaflet and chordae rupture in a 36-year-old woman with a history of rheumatic fever 26 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image shows superior bulging of the anterior leaflet (straight arrow) resulting in a coaptation defect (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 8) shows a large coaptation defect (arrow), a result of diffuse prolapse of the anterior mitral valve leaflet <i>(A)</i>. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c)</b> Coronal volume-rendered CT image (Movie 8) shows rupture (arrowhead) and diffuse thickening of the chordae tendineae. <i>A</i> = anterior mitral valve leaflet, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows rupture of the chordae tendineae (arrowhead) and diffuse thickening of the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve <i>(A)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig12d.jpeg" height="724" width="911" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Rheumatic mitral valve disease with diffuse prolapse of the anterior mitral valve leaflet and chordae rupture in a 36-year-old woman with a history of rheumatic fever 26 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image shows superior bulging of the anterior leaflet (straight arrow) resulting in a coaptation defect (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 8) shows a large coaptation defect (arrow), a result of diffuse prolapse of the anterior mitral valve leaflet <i>(A)</i>. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(c)</b> Coronal volume-rendered CT image (Movie 8) shows rupture (arrowhead) and diffuse thickening of the chordae tendineae. <i>A</i> = anterior mitral valve leaflet, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows rupture of the chordae tendineae (arrowhead) and diffuse thickening of the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve <i>(A)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig13a.jpeg" height="992" width="846" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Infective endocarditis with vegetation in a 36-year-old man who presented with general weakness, fever, and chills 3 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows nodular thickening of the anterior mitral valve leaflet (straight arrow) and thickening of the posterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead) and subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image of the mitral valve shows that the middle and medial scallops are involved (straight arrow). Subvalvular nodular thickening (curved arrow) is also seen. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 9) shows diffuse thickening and prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (arrow) and the posterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows vegetation (straight arrow) in the mitral valve anterior leaflet (A2 and A3) and thickening of the subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). These findings correlate well with those seen at CT. Posterior mitral valve involvement was also confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig13b.jpeg" height="992" width="629" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Infective endocarditis with vegetation in a 36-year-old man who presented with general weakness, fever, and chills 3 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows nodular thickening of the anterior mitral valve leaflet (straight arrow) and thickening of the posterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead) and subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image of the mitral valve shows that the middle and medial scallops are involved (straight arrow). Subvalvular nodular thickening (curved arrow) is also seen. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 9) shows diffuse thickening and prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (arrow) and the posterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows vegetation (straight arrow) in the mitral valve anterior leaflet (A2 and A3) and thickening of the subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). These findings correlate well with those seen at CT. Posterior mitral valve involvement was also confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig13c.jpeg" height="533" width="579" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Infective endocarditis with vegetation in a 36-year-old man who presented with general weakness, fever, and chills 3 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows nodular thickening of the anterior mitral valve leaflet (straight arrow) and thickening of the posterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead) and subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image of the mitral valve shows that the middle and medial scallops are involved (straight arrow). Subvalvular nodular thickening (curved arrow) is also seen. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 9) shows diffuse thickening and prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (arrow) and the posterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows vegetation (straight arrow) in the mitral valve anterior leaflet (A2 and A3) and thickening of the subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). These findings correlate well with those seen at CT. Posterior mitral valve involvement was also confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig13d.jpeg" height="533" width="897" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span> Infective endocarditis with vegetation in a 36-year-old man who presented with general weakness, fever, and chills 3 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows nodular thickening of the anterior mitral valve leaflet (straight arrow) and thickening of the posterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead) and subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image of the mitral valve shows that the middle and medial scallops are involved (straight arrow). Subvalvular nodular thickening (curved arrow) is also seen. Dashed line = mitral annulus plane, <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Surgeon’s view (Movie 9) shows diffuse thickening and prolapse of the A2 and A3 scallops (arrow) and the posterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead). <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows vegetation (straight arrow) in the mitral valve anterior leaflet (A2 and A3) and thickening of the subvalvular apparatus (curved arrow). These findings correlate well with those seen at CT. Posterior mitral valve involvement was also confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig14a.jpeg" height="954" width="632" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve and mitral regurgitation in a 42-year-old man. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows severe hypertrophy of the left ventricular wall causing collapse of the left ventricular lumen, systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve (arrow) resulting in a coaptation defect (curved arrow), and mild thickening (arrowhead) of the posterior mitral valve leaflet. <b>(b)</b> Cardiac magnetic resonance image shows both mitral regurgitation (*) and flow acceleration in the left ventricular outflow tract (arrow) (Movie 10).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346130146/asset/images/large/rg.346130146.fig14b.jpeg" height="954" width="693" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve and mitral regurgitation in a 42-year-old man. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image of the mitral valve shows severe hypertrophy of the left ventricular wall causing collapse of the left ventricular lumen, systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve (arrow) resulting in a coaptation defect (curved arrow), and mild thickening (arrowhead) of the posterior mitral valve leaflet. <b>(b)</b> Cardiac magnetic resonance image shows both mitral regurgitation (*) and flow acceleration in the left ventricular outflow tract (arrow) (Movie 10).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346130146&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Otto CM, Bonow RO. <em>Valvular heart disease</em>. In: Bonow RO, ed. Braunwald’s heart disease: <em>a textbook of cardiovascular medicine</em>. 9th ed. Philadelphia, Pa: Elsevier Saunders, 2012; 1468–1539.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Braunwald%E2%80%99s+heart+disease&amp;author=CM+Otto&amp;author=RO+Bonow&amp;publication_year=2012&amp;pages=1468-1539">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Nkomo VT, Gardin JM, Skelton TN, Gottdiener JS, Scott CG, Enriquez-Sarano M. Burden of valvular heart diseases: a population-based study. <em>Lancet</em> 2006;368(9540):1005–1011.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(06)69208-8">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16980116/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Burden+of+valvular+heart+diseases%3A+a+population-based+study&amp;author=VT+Nkomo&amp;author=JM+Gardin&amp;author=TN+Skelton&amp;a